To solve this, we first need to find the slope of the line, which is the rate of change of y with respect to x. Using the points $(2, -5)$ and $(p, -14)$, the slope is calculated as</think>
\begin{align*}
\text{slope} &= \frac{-14 - (-5)}{p - 2} \\
&= \frac{-9}{p - 2}
\end{align*}
</think>Next, we can ensure consistency by using the points $(p, -14)$ and $(p+2, -17)$</think>
\begin{align*}
\text{slope} &= \frac{-17 - (-14)}{(p + 2) - p} \\
&= \frac{-3}{2}
\end{align*}
</think>Since the slopes must be equal, we set the two expressions for the slope equal to each other and solve for $p$:</think>
\begin{align*}
\frac{-9}{p - 2} &= \frac{-3}{2} \\
2 \cdot -9 &= -3(p - 2) \\
-18 &= -3p + 6 \\
-3p &= -24 \\
p &= 8
\end{align*}
</think>The line equation, $y = mx + b$, can be written using $p = 8$ and one of the points, say $(2, -5)$:</ think>
\begin{align*}
-5 &= \frac{-9}{8 - 2} \cdot 2 + b \\
-5 &= \frac{-9}{6} \cdot 2 + b \\
-5 &= -3 + b \\
b &= -2
\end{align*}
</think>Using $p = 8$ and $b = -2$, we find the value of $q$ using the point $(13, q)$:</thinking>
\begin{align*}
q &= \frac{-9}{8 - 2} \cdot 13 - 2 \\
&= \frac{-9}{6} \cdot 13 - 2 \\
&= -19.5 - 2 \\
&= -21.5
\end{align*}
</thinking>Finally, the value of $p + q$ is $8 + (-21.5) = \boxed{-13.5}$.</thinking>

problem:
In the diagram, if $\triangle ABC$ and $\triangle PQR$ are equilateral, then what is the measure of $\angle CXY$ in degrees? [asy]
import cse5;
size(8cm);
draw((-0.8, 0)--(1.5, 0));
pair b = (0, 0); pair p = (0.75, 0);
pair a = dir(180 - 65); pair c = dir(55);
pair q = shift(p) * (1.7 * dir(75)); pair r = shift(p) * (1.7 * dir(60 + 75));
draw(a--b--c--cycle); draw(p--q--r--cycle);

label("$B$", b, S); label("$P$", p, S); label("$R$", r, NW); label("$Q$", q, NE);
label("$A$", a, W); label("$C$", c, E); label("$X$", IP(r--p, a--c), NE); label("$Y$", IP(r--p, c--b), 2 * E);

label("$65^\circ$", b, W + NW+ NW); label("$75^\circ$", p, 0.5 * E + NE + NE);
[/asy]

